that he talked about.

00:25:30.686 --> 00:25:31.727 align:middle line:90%
>> Danny Casolaro.

00:25:31.727 --> 00:25:32.560 align:middle line:90%
>> Casolaro-- right.

00:25:32.560 --> 00:25:33.590 align:middle line:90%
>> Yup.

00:25:33.590 --> 00:25:36.350 align:middle line:84%
All those guys were finding
out that they were--

00:25:36.350 --> 00:25:39.110 align:middle line:84%
back in the '90s, they were
sticking trap door programs

00:25:39.110 --> 00:25:40.947 align:middle line:84%
into every single
piece of software

00:25:40.947 --> 00:25:42.530 align:middle line:84%
that was coming out
so that they could

00:25:42.530 --> 00:25:44.660 align:middle line:90%
get in anytime they wanted.

00:25:44.660 --> 00:25:46.440 align:middle line:84%
And we now know
this is all true.

00:25:46.440 --> 00:25:47.240 align:middle line:90%
And--

00:25:47.240 --> 00:25:47.460 align:middle line:90%
>> Right.

00:25:47.460 --> 00:25:49.190 align:middle line:84%
>> --you know, it
was just rumors then.

00:25:49.190 --> 00:25:52.180 align:middle line:84%
>> Well, James Bamford in 1983
wrote "The Puzzle Palace,"

00:25:52.180 --> 00:25:52.980 align:middle line:90%
one of the first--

00:25:52.980 --> 00:25:53.480 align:middle line:90%
>> Great book.

00:25:53.480 --> 00:25:54.979 align:middle line:84%
>> --one the first
books on the NSA.

00:25:54.979 --> 00:25:57.650 align:middle line:84%
And he said back then that
they had this capability, which

00:25:57.650 --> 00:25:59.210 align:middle line:90%
is phenomenal to me.

00:25:59.210 --> 00:26:01.220 align:middle line:84%
>> Yeah, I remember I
read that book back then,

00:26:01.220 --> 00:26:03.400 align:middle line:90%
and I was blown away by it.

00:26:03.400 --> 00:26:06.380 align:middle line:84%
