get the hybrid, the idea

00:27:07.670 --> 00:27:09.860 align:middle line:84%
of the guy who's going to
bridge these two worlds,

00:27:09.860 --> 00:27:12.380 align:middle line:84%
kind of like Jesus is
both human and divine.

00:27:12.380 --> 00:27:13.580 align:middle line:90%
And he bridges this gap.

00:27:13.580 --> 00:27:16.760 align:middle line:84%
And so we're going to get
the half-cyborg, half-human

00:27:16.760 --> 00:27:17.580 align:middle line:90%
character here.

00:27:17.580 --> 00:27:19.135 align:middle line:84%
So let's look at
"No Second Chances."

00:27:19.135 --> 00:27:22.050 align:middle line:10%
>> Our best machines had failed
time and again to complete

00:27:22.050 --> 00:27:22.850 align:middle line:10%
the mission.

00:27:22.850 --> 00:27:24.570 align:middle line:10%
Something was missing.

00:27:24.570 --> 00:27:27.146 align:middle line:10%
We had to think radically.

00:27:27.146 --> 00:27:29.480 align:middle line:10%
And so we made you.

00:27:29.480 --> 00:27:33.220 align:middle line:10%
We created the perfect
infiltration machine.

00:27:33.220 --> 00:27:36.760 align:middle line:10%
You, Marcus, you
did what Skynet has

00:27:36.760 --> 00:27:39.676 align:middle line:10%
failed to do for so many years.

00:27:39.676 --> 00:27:41.610 align:middle line:10%
You killed John Connor.

00:27:41.610 --> 00:27:45.500 align:middle line:84%
>> Here's Sam Worthington
playing the savior once again,

00:27:45.500 --> 00:27:47.240 align:middle line:84%
the guy who bridges
these two worlds.

00:27:47.240 --> 00:27:50.570 align:middle line:84%
And we find out, interestingly,
that the weakness

00:27:50.570 --> 00:27:53.120 align:middle line:84%
of the terminators
was that they didn't

00:27:53.120 --> 00:27:54.650 align:middle line:90%
have empathy and human emotion.

00:27:54.650 --> 00:27:57.634 align:middle line:84%
They didn't understand,
you know, how to--

00:27:57.634 --> 00:28:01.070 align:middle line:84%
to integrate that into
their attack pattern.

00:28:01.070 --> 00:28:03.200 align:middle line:84%
And so they create
this character

00:28:03.200 --> 00:28:05.480 align:middle line:84%
that they think will
be kind of this spy

00:28:05.480 --> 00:28:08.070 align:middle line:84%
to infiltrate the humans,
which is the same role that he

00:28:08.070 --> 00:28:08.870 align:middle line:90%
plays--

00:28:08.870 --> 00:28:09.180 align:middle line:90%
>> In "Avatar."

00:28:09.180 --> 00:28:10.627 align:middle line:90%
>> --in "Avatar," right?

00:28:10.627 --> 00:28:12.710 align:middle line:84%
It's just that Cameron's
got a lot of these things

00:28:12.710 --> 00:28:13.584 align:middle line:90%
on his mind, I guess.

00:28:13.584 --> 00:28:14.540 align:middle line:90%
Right?

00:28:14.540 --> 00:28:16.220 align:middle line:84%
What happens is that
it's the reverse.

00:28:16.220 --> 00:28:18.440 align:middle line:84%
He's actually-- because
he's this-- this bridge

00:28:18.440 --> 00:28:20.660 align:middle line:84%
between these two worlds
and he has free will because

00:28:20.660 --> 00:28:24.050 align:middle line:84%
of his emotions and you
know, empathy, he's able

00:28:24.050 --> 00:28:25.802 align:middle line:90%
to, therefore, defeat Skynet.

00:28:25.802 --> 00:28:28.010 align:middle line:84%
>> It is kind of crazy how
close that is to "Avatar."

00:28:28.010 --> 00:28:28.500 align:middle line:90%
>> [LAUGHING] Right?

00:28:28.500 --> 00:28:28.790 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:28:28.790 --> 00:28:30.440 align:middle line:90%
>> I mean, it's really crazy--

00:28:30.440 --> 00:28:33.440 align:middle line:84%
both Sam Worthington,
same year both films

00:28:33.440 --> 00:28:35.270 align:middle line:84%
came out, with
almost the same plot.

00:28:35.270 --> 00:28:36.260 align:middle line:90%
Very strange.

00:28:36.260 --> 00:28:38.550 align:middle line:84%
And Cameron had
influences on all that.

00:28:38.550 --> 00:28:40.850 align:middle line:90%
So it really makes you wonder.

00:28:40.850 --> 00:28:43.040 align:middle line:84%
But yeah, that was a great
ending to the series.

00:28:43.040 --> 00:28:45.470 align:middle line:84%
I don't know-- I haven't
seen the new one yet.

00:28:45.470 --> 00:28:47.030 align:middle line:90%
So I can't comment on it.

00:28:47.030 --> 00:28:52.100 align:middle line:84%
But I thought that the ending
of that series was really good.

00:28:52.100 --> 00:28:54.550 align:middle line:84%
>> I think, really, the
best part of the new one--

00:28:54.550 --> 00:28:56.400 align:middle line:84%
it didn't do that
well critically.

00:28:56.400 --> 00:28:58.700 align:middle line:84%
And I think it was
mediocre box office.

00:28:58.700 --> 00:29:02.000 align:middle line:10%
But the most relevant
aspect of the last one,

00:29:02.000 --> 00:29:06.630 align:middle line:10%
"Genesis," was that it was back
to the time loop narrative.

00:29:06.630 --> 00:29:09.290 align:middle line:10%
But what happened was
that they literally put,

00:29:09.290 --> 00:29:12.200 align:middle line:10%
you know, our tech
devices that we all

00:29:12.200 --> 00:29:18.100 align:middle line:10%
carry as the means by which the
awakening of Skynet happens.

00:29:18.100 --> 00:29:20.700 align:middle line:84%
And so they actually have all
of the humans opting into it.

00:29:20.700 --> 00:29:22.170 align:middle line:90%
You have to opt into it, right?

00:29:22.170 --> 00:29:22.970 align:middle line:90%
>> Wow.

00:29:22.970 --> 00:29:27.270 align:middle line:84%
>> And if you opt into it, then
it sort of transfers the right

00:29:27.270 --> 00:29:30.580 align:middle line:84%
for Skynet to rule
over to this--

00:29:30.580 --> 00:29:32.450 align:middle line:90%
this ethereal AI entity.

00:29:32.450 --> 00:29:35.520 align:middle line:84%
>> And that seems to be also one
of the rules of the Illuminati,

00:29:35.520 --> 00:29:37.750 align:middle line:84%
that they have to get
you to tacitly agree--

00:29:37.750 --> 00:29:38.550 align:middle line:90%
>> Exactly.

00:29:38.550 --> 00:29:41.220 align:middle line:84%
>> --to their plan, or the
plan cannot be executed.

00:29:41.220 --> 00:29:43.084 align:middle line:90%
So that's very interesting.

00:29:43.084 --> 00:29:44.250 align:middle line:90%
Well, these films are great.

00:29:44.250 --> 00:29:46.560 align:middle line:84%
I mean, you know, they're
well worth watching,

00:29:46.560 --> 00:29:48.160 align:middle line:84%
all the way from
beginning to the end.

00:29:48.160 --> 00:29:52.230 align:middle line:84%
And they're advancing
a narrative that we all

00:29:52.230 --> 00:29:53.120 align:middle line:90%
need to think about.

00:29:53.120 --> 00:29:56.730 align:middle line:84%
>> Yeah, I see them, too,
as predecessors too a couple

00:29:56.730 --> 00:29:57.750 align:middle line:90%
recent films--

00:29:57.750 --> 00:30:00.240 align:middle line:84%
more recent films--
that are very important,

00:30:00.240 --> 00:30:01.170 align:middle line:90%
like "Ex Machina"--

00:30:01.170 --> 00:30:02.160 align:middle line:90%
>> Yes.

00:30:02.160 --> 00:30:04.390 align:middle line:10%
>> --and "Her," the
Spike Jones film.

00:30:04.390 --> 00:30:05.190 align:middle line:10%
>> "Her."

00:30:05.190 --> 00:30:07.080 align:middle line:10%
>> Both of these contain
the same warning,

00:30:07.080 --> 00:30:10.800 align:middle line:10%
the same narrative or threat,
